## Did MCTS See Any Success?

Short answer: it showed promise at small sample sizes but collapsed at proper sample sizes.

- **v1 (exact flow scorer as leaf):** looked great at n=20 (80% vs schmeekler) but collapsed to parity at n=50. The de-meaned correction showed zero variance — the scoring was correct but the candidate set was so small (0-4 moves per turn) that re-ranking them made no difference.

- **v2 (true depth-2 beam + state-advancement opponent model):** showed +2pp at n=20, parity at n=50. Same problem — the engine already filters so aggressively that there's nothing meaningful to search over.

So MCTS didn't fail because the algorithm was wrong. It failed because the **engine pre-filters to near-determinism before search even starts.** You can't build a meaningful search tree when 64/133 turns have zero candidates and 47 have exactly one.

This is why the value function changes the game — instead of re-ranking the engine's 0-4 approved candidates, it evaluates moves the engine currently rejects. That's a fundamentally different problem.

## What If the Gym Is Still Wrong?

This is the right question to keep asking and the honest answer is: the gym is still imperfect, but you have two protection mechanisms.

**Protection 1 — The gym-vs-live calibration is improving.** You now have two real live data points: comet_reaper at 1245 and schmeekler at 1075. The gym correctly orders them after the anchor fixes. It's not perfect but it's directionally trustworthy for large differences.

**Protection 2 — The value function sidesteps the gym problem entirely.** Its fidelity is measured on real episode outcomes, not gym results. The fidelity probe asks "does V rank real winning positions above real losing positions from downloaded episodes?" — that's ground truth, not a proxy. If V passes fidelity on real data, you can submit with confidence regardless of what the gym says.

This is actually the strongest argument for the value function path: it's the only improvement mechanism whose quality signal comes from real competition data rather than your local approximation.

